column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Our driver was traveling NW in the right lane on Mount Holly Rd (NC 27) and entered intersection on a green light. The other vehicle, traveling SE on NC 27 and attempting to access I-485, turned left on a flashing yellow arrow and collided with our tractor unit. Our driver attempted to stop to avoid making contact with the other vehicle while continuing forward in the right lane, but making contact with the right-hand guardrail. The collision damaged the pitman arm on our unit's steering control forcing it into a hard left turn and coming to rest after separation of the tank trailer from the tractor. Tank trailer overturned. Tractor unit remained upright. Both parties were transported by ambulance, treated for minor injuries and released.
column169: As always, reinforce defensive driving during and after initial training for new drivers along with refresher training for experienced drivers.

column168: On 9/14/2018, the FRA Hazmat Inspector was inspecting our Gambrinus Yard in Canton Ohio and found that tank car UTLX 910785 was leaking from the Vapor valve.  He found that the valve handle was not tight and  was leaking out from the valve plug.  Jeff Clapper, Locomotive Supt. with the WLE was called to  respond to the car. When he arrived, he found that the valve handle was indeed not tight.  He  tightened the valve handle and the leak stopped.  He also noticed that the valve plug was less  than tool tight.  He tightened the valve plug and also reinstalled the cap on the  magnetic gauging device.  Seal number 0218347 was removed from the protective housing by the FRA.  FRA installed seal number DOT FRA 56005.  Jeff Clapper installed seal number 971759 on  the protective housing after the repairs were made.
column169: Better car securement procedures need followed.

column168: On 9/12/2018 at approximately 5:34am, our employee was operating truck 402 & trailer 42   traveling on Round Knob Road, Greenville TN. column168: Mr Charles Haydu tendered shipment to KTN. 2 of 8 contained undeclared hazmat.  Ammunition UN 0012 Cartridge small arms. , matches,  and handwarmers (undecided if hazmat).    At original time of tender his friend Skip was allowing him to use his known shipper number and  the discussion as to nature of goods caused me to share with them a recent GIR with  undeclared hazmat with other shippers in the same week.  We talked about the  difference between ammo in checked baggage and cargo.  Mr. Haydu took less than 5 minutes  going thru his 2 pc and determined he removed 1 box of ammo.  His friend Skip asked him  specifically if he was sure.  He answered in the affirmative.      At time of x-ray screening  agent Sue Vandorp brought ot my attention both bags contained ammo.   I performed a  25 min physical inspection and found 3 boxes of 20 each rifle cartridges, along with 4 pack  of matches.   (hand warmers, undetermined hazmat).  I contacted shipper , discussed  issue, he found his known shipper number and the awb was changed to reflect his own  CID 20663.   He's been advised report to FAA pending, and once I received permission to release  from FAA inspector I would advise
column169: Frequent issue.  Shippers do not understand difference between passenger allowance of ammo and cargo acceptance.    When you attempt to educate shipper complacent and in a hurry.  Shipper does  not believe ammo as a true danger.     Posters in office should be in color, and specific.  Maybe the possible  specific fine on them so it is clear to a shipper.

column168: On 9/9/2018, a Non-Accident Release involving AEX 15137 at Radnor Yard, a loaded rail car of Aluminum Smelting By-Products, was discovered leaking ammonia vapors from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Scepter Inc., was notified via 3E Report 1381234. Joseph McCann, with CSX’s Hazardous Materials Team, as well as Marion Environmental, Inc. (MEI), a CSXT emergency response contractor, were dispatched to the scene and found the release was due to a faulty hopper cover. The hopper covers ribs were displaced, tearing the cover, and allowing rain water to come in contact with the water reactive lading.  The introduction of water to the lading liberated and released ammonia vapors.  The response crew was able to make temporary repair to the cover and secure the load.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to Mr. John Bond, with Scepter.  The car was then released for transportation.

column168: Just after 9pm CST on 9/15/18 dispatcher Bobby Salyer received a text from driver Jeff Wright that read, 'accident'. He then received a call from 911 dispatch letting Bobby know that an ambulance was en route to Jeff. Meanwhile, dispatcher Bill Couch contacted Morgan letting him know that she needed to call Bobby. Morgan reached out to Bobby, who, while on the line with Morgan, received a subsequent call from a responding officer, Officer Hubbard. Bobby provided Morgan with Officer Hubbard’s number. Officer Hubbard connected Morgan with Sargeant Gates, and local Emergency Responder Alton Haines. She was informed that there was a slow leak and that a response unit was needed. (It would later be discovered that there was another breach in the tanker.) Morgan utilized AIG's PIER program to get a unit on site. PIER's resource, Clean Harbors, led by District Manager Brian Overmyer, was sent on-site. During this time, Bobby updated Morgan that Jeff suffered a broken cheekbone, but was okay. Regarding vehicle damage, at this point, the truck and trailer are considered totaled. On 9/16, Brian Overmyer reported to Morgan that Clean Harbors was able to vacuum off approximately 7000 gallons of product from the tanker truck, up from the original report of 6500 gallons. Based on this information, it was initially estimated that between 300 and 900 gallons of product was released.  The morning of 9/17/18, Morgan was notified by Alton Haines and resident Michael Floyd that the incident occurred on and near properties with wells. Eco would contract with environmental consultants to perform soil and water monitoring at the site. Rich Luzinski, terminal coordinator Cara Waters, and Morgan worked together to collect documents such as truck and trailer registration, Peoplenet logs, BOL, and engine data. Peoplenet data indicates that Jeff was not in violation of any DOT HOS regulations. Engine data indicates, within the two minutes prior to the accident, Jeff was driving  between 48 and 63 mph. Prior to reading 0 mph, the last five seconds of the onboard event recorder indicate 63, 53, 47, 35, 41 mph. Later that morning, Rich Luzinski and Morgan Greenwood called Jeff Wright. Jeff indicated he was in pain and that he had lost his hearing aide and glasses. He also said that the seatbelt did not catch. He had a broken cheekbone and eye socket and stitches in his forehead. He had been released from the hospital at approximately 7am CST. Rich asked Jeff what happened that night and Jeff expressed that if there had been a sign at that curve ‘this wouldn’t have happened’. Jeff told Rich ‘ask any driver, everyone knows about that curve’. Rich asked what the speed limit was, Jeff indicated he did not know. Rich asked how the conditions were and Jeff said the road was wet. Rich asked Jeff if he felt he was driving at a safe speed given the conditions (tropical storm from Hurricane Florence). Jeff again referenced the curve. On 9/18/18, Morgan received the post-accident Driver/
column169: For Eco-Energy, this incident confirms that speed management must be an integral part of our driver training and disciplinary program. Part of this training must also reference weather-appropriate speed management. I will be working on a revamped speed management training to deliver to our drivers and also work with driver managers to expedite the disciplinary process for speeding infractions.

column168: On 9/19/2017, the FRA took exception to SHPX 215032 a residue tank car Acetic Acid, at Kingsport, TN, found to have a multiple mounting bolts on the liquid line valve flange to be less than tool tight.  These loose valve mounts bolts also resulting in a Non-Accident Release (NAR) of product vapor.  The car was isolated and BP North America  was notified via CHEMTREC Report 2018-0919-00169.  Marion Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and confirmed all 4 liquid line valve mounting bolts were less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper- Mr. Trevor Lapier. Contractor personnel tightened all bolts which stopped the release of product vapor. The car was held out of transportation pending a One Time Movement Approval from the FRA.

column168: On 9/1/18 one of our Heritage drivers noticed a trailer leaking liquid out in the back lot. The driver immediately notified the acting supervisor in the sampling department. The acting supervisor then went out to the lot to investigate. He determined that one of the drums in the trailer was leaking a substance onto the blacktop. He applied floor dry material on the spill and then went inside of the trailer to determine which drum was leaking. Once in the trailer, he determined that the leak was somewhere in the front of the trailer. He couldn't safely determine exactly which drum was leaking, so he applied some floor dry material to the floor of the trailer which stopped liquid from leaking onto the black top.He then notified the Operations Manager for Heritage Transport to report the spill. The Op erations Manager then called the EHS Manager to inform him of the spill. The EHS Manager responded to the scene to supervise the cleanup and to investigate the incident. The EHS Manager determined that the trailer could be safely moved to the loading dock for unloading. Once the trailer was unloaded, the leaking drum was discovered. It was a thirty gallon plastic drum of Nitric Acid and Chromium. The drum had over pressurized and split in two places in the front of the drum. The splits were vertical and ran about eight to ten inches long. It is estimated that the drum originally held about 15 gallons of liquid. The splits in the drum released about 5 gallons or 30 pounds of liquid on the black top and inside the trailer. The leaking drum was placed in an overpack drum and the floor dry on the blacktop was swept up and properly disposed of.

column168: FUEL HAULER WAS OFF-LOADING 1000 GALLONS OF DIESEL INTO A BELOW GROUND 2000 GALLON TANK. THE TANK HAD 740 GALLONS ALREADY IN IT. THIS IS A GRAVITY FEED DROP FROM THE TRAILER TO BELOW GROUND TANK. THE FLAPPER VALUE ON THE INLET LINE WAS SET AT 85% ALMOST ALL OTHER GAS STATIONS ARE AT 90%. THE DRIVER KNEW THE 1000 GALLONS WOULD FIT AT 90% HE DID NOT KNOWN THIS STORE WAS AT 85%. THE FLOW STOPPED WHEN IT HIT THE FLAPPER VALUE WHICH CAUSED THE HOSE TO BOUNCE. THE DOWN SPOUT CONNECTED TO THE INLET TUBE BOUNCED OFF THE FITTING. IT WAS IDENTIFIED THAT THIS DOWN SPOUT BOUNCED OFF THE FITTING. IT WAS IDENTIFIED THAT THIS DOWN SPOUT WAS WORN AND DID NOT HATCH PROPERLY - 47 GALLONS WAS RELEASED.
column169: ALL EMPLOYEES IN WASHINGTON HAVE BEEN ADVISED OF THE FLAPPER GETTING FOR THIS STORE. DISPATCH HAS BEEN ADVISED NOT TO SEND MORE THAN 1,500 GALLONS TO THIS STORE. ALL DOWN SPOUTS FOR OUR COMPANY HAVE BEEN EXAMINED AND THOSE THAT WERE WORN HAVE BEEN REPLACED.

column168: Driver was on a slight downhill canyon road that had turns that ranged from 35mph to 55mph.He was very familiar with this road, as he has traveled it hundreds of times delivering loads for us for the last 12 years.  According to the video we recovered from the accident, the inside view showed a behavior that is consistent with fatigue. He was holding his speed just fine, until the last half mile, where the speed slowly increased as he approached the last two downhill curves. Both curves had a posting of 35mph, and he allowed his speed to creep up to 50mph. The trailer rolled first, pulling over the truck. The fuel that released from the truck tank, leaked out the dome lids. The fuel that released from the trailer, was from a large hole, caused by the guard rail when the trailer rolled and struck it. Since both cargo tanks were laying on their sides, the releasing fuel stopped in less than 30 minutes. Within 1 minute of the accident, witnesses called 911& Emergency responders were immediately dispatched. The remaining fuel was removed, and the truck & trailer was up righted. The contaminated dirt was removed and transported to a recycling facility, and roadway that was affected, was re-paved.
column169: Williams Tank Lines conducts 6 Safety Meetings a year for each one of our 8 Terminals, where all topics are discussed, including Defensive Driving & driving fatigued. We have had a program in place for several years, where Terminal Managers review video captured by the on-board camera's, to alert us of un-safe behaviors. This driver had a clean 12 year record with the company, and had been on the "Day Shift" 5am to 5pm for many years. During our investigative interview of the driver, it was discovered that he had stayed up later than normal to watch Thursday Night Football, which we feel was a major contributor to his fatigue. The cargo tanks are sound equipment, and short of making all tanks out of heavy gauge steel, which would be impractical, no re-design is necessary. One cannot remove the human element from our industry, all we can do is continue our frequent education to our employees on the need for proper rest.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: UTLX 664690 was observed with product on the side of the tank. It released from the liquid valve at  the pipe threads. The valve was less then tool tight. The valve was removed, threads cleaned,  Teflon tape applied, then the valve was reinstalled. This stopped the release.

UTLX 631021 was observed with product on the side of the tank. The leak point was at the pressure  plate and nozzle connection. 5 out of 12 pressure plate bolts were less then tool tight.  The bolts moved about 1/8 of a turn each. This stopped the release.

column168: GATX 22178 was observed with product on the top and side of the tank. The leak was from the  manway. 5 out of 6 manway hinged swing bolts were less then tool-tight. The manway gasket was  deteriorated. The gasket was replaced and the manway was secured. This stopped the release.

column168: At 0430 ET, ERTS received a call from John Jansen of XPO Logistics - XMP terminal regarding a spill at the terminal. It was reported at 0320 ET, terminal personnel were unloading trailer #3154829 (inbound from XDM terminal) when they discovered one pallet containing several 5 gallon pails of UN2735 "Elastacoat 2 part Epoxy Waterproofing Hardener" AND of non-regulated "Elastacoat 2 part Epoxy Waterproofing Resin " that appear to be damaged due to improper loading / stacking of the freight causing the pails to fall and leak a few ounces of material onto other containers. ERTS instructed terminal personnel to stand down due to containers falling over and potential for spill to increase and as a safety hazard. Contractor confirmed 0.5 gallons of material released to the trailer from (3) 5 gallon plastic pails. Contractor used purple power neutralizer to clean up the hazardous material and overpacked it into a 55 gal poly drum. No waterways, soils or drains were impacted by this release. There is no further clean up needed.

column168: At 1841 ET, ERTS received a call from Christopher Harman of XPO Logistics regarding a spill at the terminal. At 1815 ET, terminal personnel were unloading trailer #5631074 (last loaded at the NWI terminal) when approximately 5 gallons of UN1993 "Mineral Spirits" leaked out of a 350 Gallon metal tote due to the cap falling off the tote. Terminal personnel secured the cap back on the tote and the tote is secure at this time. Totes were believed to have contained residual material and shipped as empty. ERTS reviewed safety concerns with the material and confirmed that terminal personnel can clean the release with the appropriate PPE and waste containers.  Terminal personnel have placed all impacted absorbents into (1) 20 Gallon Steel Drum and sent the tote on to the consignee. There were no storm drains, waterways, or soils impacted by this release. All cleanup has been handled.

Mike White with XPO Logistics (LSL Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a UN1505-Sodium persulfate "Sodium Persulfate Regular" release. During unloading operations, (1) 2204 pound super sac was punctured by a pallet releasing approximately 1 pound to the dock floor. ERTS dispatched USES to clean the release and and to transfer the rest of the product from the damaged super sack to be sent on. The contractor generated (4) 5-gallon poly drums of the swept contaminated product, (1) 5-gallon drum of the contaminated product and poly sheeting,  and (1) 95-gallon poly drum containing the damaged super sack, spent PPE and poly sheeting. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted.

column168: At 2048 ERTS was contacted by Mike Casey of XPO Logistics XMD about a cargo release. It was reported that due to a forklift accident approximately 8 ounces of UN1210, 3, II IC-2BK003 released from a 2 gallon plastic jug. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the dock. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and he felt comfortable cleaning the release with granular absorbents and the proper PPE. The released product and 2 gallon plastic jug will be placed in a 5 gal metal drum. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release.

At 2016 ET, ERTS received a call from Jeff Bowen of XPO Logistics - NCH terminal regarding a spill at the terminal in Charlotte, NC.  It was reported at 2010 ET, terminal personnel punctured one - 330 Gallon Poly tote of UN1840 "Zinc Chloride" resulting in the release of approximately 1 quart to 1 gallon of material to the dock floor. The forklift blade was left inside of the tote to contain the release. Contractor got on site and determined there was about 25 gallons released, then by the time the forklift blade was removed from the tote 120 gallons released, but only impacting the dock floor. Contractor used soda ash to neutralize the released material before overpacking waste material into (1) 55 gal poly drum, (4) 30 gal poly drums, and (1) 95 gal poly drum. The remaining liquid material was transferred to a 275 gal poly tote. All clean up was handled at that time, there is no required remediation. There were no storm drains, waterways or soil impacted by the release.

column168: Sept. 20, 2018:  At approximately 8:07AM, I contacted CR Trainmaster J. Higgins, who advised that CR crew of the CA11-20 reported tank car GATX 10510, 5-compartment car of Gasoline, was leaking at the bottom outlet from compartment 5.  They noted while performing switching operations on the Pennsgrove Secondary and Gibbstown Siding.  Mr. Higgins placed a 5-gallon plastic pail under the outlet to contain the material and also layed absorbant pads and boom around the area of the valve.   CR A. Richter, Risk Management, contacted CHEMTREC to report (#2018 092000081).  CR Operations Support notified Greenwich Township FD.  Further inspection by CR's A. Richter found the leak at the bottom outlet on compartment 5 due to the top operated bottom outlet valve was not completely closed.  Noted the packing gland nut for said valve, up top, was not tool tight.  Valve was operated from the top and closed, whereby stopping the release.  The packing gland nut for the valve operating rod was also made tool tight.  Bottom of valve was inspected and no exceptions were noted.  Bottom outlet closure plug and cap were removed to allow captured material to drain in the 5-gallon pail, and then were reapplied and made tool tight.  Car was ok to be shipped to original destination.

column168: On September 22, 2018, at 0100 ET, XPO Logistics Terminal UPW located at 2121 Garland St., in Pasco, WA 99301 experienced a release of hazardous UN1263 "Axalta Low Sheen Sealer Top Coat". It was stated that approximately 20-gallons released from (1) 55-gallon metal drum due to a forklift puncture. Terminal personnel stated the release was confined to the dock floor. Absorbents were place on the spill to clean and contain it. Jackson's Clearwater Environmental were dispatched to respond to the spill to provide over packing operations. The contractors arrived on site on September 22, 2018, at 0745 ET and utilized floor dry to clean the release. The contractors generated (1) 85-gallon metal drum containing the damaged drum and (1) 95-gallon poly drum containing impacted absorbents and debris.  All waste was left on site in the terminals waste area for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: RECOMMEND THAT THE SHIPPER ONLY USE NEW BOXES FOR HAZMAT SHIPMENTS AND THAT THOSE BOXES HAVE ALL THE REQUIRED MARKINGS FOR THE HAZMATS BEING SHIPPED.

The trailer was washed out before going to Quantum for the pickup.  The driver didn't check if the manways were secured before picking up nitric acid.  He also didn't check the manways before departing to come home.  Nitric acid splashed out of the tank when he hit the brakes hard on I-10.  Some spilled on the ground and some made contact with a couple cars driving by.  The driver stopped and used his spill kit to clean up the nitric.
column169: This was human error to not double check the manway being closed.  It's a case of retraining and reminding current and future drivers about the serious nature of the job.

column168: Hawaiian Airlines (HA) tendered a company material (COMAT) shipment for transport on HA184  04SEP2018 LIH-HNL. The shipment contained dangerous goods (DG) identified as UN3363  Dangerous Goods in Apparatus, Class 9.  The package was properly placarded and the required  paperwork was completed for the shipment including the shipper's declaration.   2. The shipment was accepted by HA Cargo in LIH and prepared for transport on HA184. 3. The cargo manifest indicated that the COMAT shipment contained DG.  4. The accompanying shipper's declaration indicated that the COMAT contained DG, and at the time  the cargo agent noticed that information was missing in the "Nature of Goods Quantity" section and the shipping label on the COMAT box had the incorrect UN number 3663 versus the correct 3363. 5. Cargo agent on duty sought assistance from Cargo Chief and Chief indicated that the shipment  contained DG and advised agent to make corrections to the AWB to include missing information and the label on the box. 6. Cargo agent made the corrections to the AWB and the shipping label. Cargo agent on duty inquired with the Cargo Chief   whether a dangerous goods checklist and Notification to Pilot in Command (NOPIC) was required. Chief cargo agent stated that the checklist and the NOPIC were not required. 7.The accepting cargo agent failed to complete the required dangerous goods checklist and  Notification to Pilot in Command (NOPIC) for the COMAT shipment. 8. The COMAT shipment was delivered to the aircraft and transported to HNL without the  required NOPIC being presented to the PIC or carried on the aircraft. 9. There was no failure of the package.  The root cause of the incident was that the Company's policy on the acceptance and handling of dangerous goods was not properly followed. According to 49 CFR 175.33 - Shipping paper and notification of pilot-in-command: The NOPIC document must be presented to the pilot in command (PIC) for signature and carried onboard the aircraft for the duration of the flight. The HA Cargo Manual Section 7.3.6.6 states that the cargo agent accepting dangerous goods will initiate a  a NOPIC. A copy of the NOPIC will be communicated to the load planning office.  The accepting cargo agent and the Chief cargo agent failed to properly follow the HA's procedures which  caused the COMAT shipment to be carried on the aircraft without the required NOPIC.
column169: The accepting cargo agent was counseled by the manager on duty on 07SEPT2018 regarding the requirements of completing the DG checklist and  NOPIC  when accepting shipments containing DG. The cargo agent is aware of the policy and procedures and is current on DG acceptance and handling training.  Due to the severity of the incident, the Chief cargo agent is required to complete the initial DG acceptance and handling training and Record of Correction Action(ROCA) was issued.

column169: AS HAZMATS ARE DELIVERED TO BELTS VIA INCOMPATIBLE CART THE MOST LIKELY SCENARIO IS THAT WHOEVER WAS UNLOADING THE CART DEPOSITED THE PACKAGE ON THE BELT WITH ENOUGH FORCE TO POP THE CAPS OFF OF TWO OF THE FOR BOTTLES IN THE BOX. THE BEST THING TO DO WOULD BE FOR MANAGEMENT TO REVIEW PROPER PACKAGE HANDLING WITH ALL EMPLOYEES WHO ARE LIKELY TO BE INVOLVED IN UNLOADING AN INCOMPATIBLE CART. PERHAPS EVEN ON A REGULAR BASIS SO EMPLOYEES WILL REMEMBER THE METHODS.

column168: During routine offloading at facility, personnel identified a container having released a portion of its contents. In proper personal protective equipment, facility personnel contained the release to the transport trailer. The impact of this release did not contaminate land, soil, water ways or storm drains. A response team was dispatched to repackage the material into UN rated containers approved for transportation to final disposal facility. A courtesy report was called into Ed Costomerius of the Utah Department of Environmental Quality.
column169: At the time of acceptance into transportation, the container was thoroughly inspected by the driver and did not present any indication that it had the potential to leak in transit. The generator was notified of the release and advised of better packing techniques for this material to prevent a release from happening again.

column168: At 1702 ET, XPO Logistics Terminal USY located at 7116 Northern Blvd in East Syracuse, NY, called ERTS to report a spill of UN3266 Super Alk Plus (AFCO 5238). It was stated that 20-gallons released from (1) 275-gallon poly tote due to other freight falling onto the tote in transit. The release impacted a 8' x 8' portion of the trailer floor and was confined to the trailer floor.  At 0830 ET, contractors arrived on site and placed absorbents down to clean the release. The contractor conducted a tote transfer for the remaining product. The contractor finished all cleanup activities at 1356 ET, and generated (6) 65-gallon poly drums of waste containing, PPE, cleanup debris, absorbents, and the cut up tote. All waste was left on site in the terminals waste area for terminal personnel to manage.

On 9/24/2018 Landstar Inway experienced a 300 gallon release of Potassium Hydroxide Solution from a 330 gallon poly tote. The release occurred when the load shifted and damaged the tote's bottom outlet valve. The release impacted the trailer, the asphalt shoulder, and grass and soil along the highway.  A clean up contractor was sent to the scene and they cleaned up the trailer, and the asphalt shoulder. The impacted soil has been marked for excavation. The contractor also identified another tote (same material) that had been damaged during the load shift, but did not leak. The material in the damaged tote was transferred to a new tote.

column168: At 1950 ET, ERTS received a call from XPO Logistics regarding a spill at the facility. It was reported at 1940 ET, terminal personnel were unloading a trailer with a drum grabber when one 55 Gallon Steel drum containing UN1104 "Amyl acetates" fell off and was damaged with a hole in the drum resulting in the release of an estimated 1 gallon of material to the dock floor. Terminal personnel immediately put the drum on its side and contained the release with granular absorbents. Terminal personnel overpacked the damaged drum into (1) 85 Gallon Steel Drum with all impacted absorbents and debris. The drum is dented and not in good condition after the damage.

At 1831 EST, Malissa Butzu with Universal Truckload Service contacted ERTS regarding a cargo release. It was reported that due to a single vehicle accident, 13-330 gallon poly totes were ejected from trailer #2066-7770. Contractor advised that after transferring the remainder of the product from the impacted totes to the new totes, only 500 gallons of product did not release. Due to this, this release exceeded the RQ.   Due to there being 13-330 gallons, it is estimated that 3,790 gallons (24,180.6 lbs) of product was lost during the accident. Contractor removed all debris offsite and utilized three roll off boxes to dispose of all soil impacted on the side of the road. The site was backfilled with clean soil and secured with grass seed and straw matting. Absorbent booms have been left in place to be checked after the next rain event. No further cleanup is required.

(2) 55-gallon steel drums of UN 1908 "CP 2043" released 80-gallons to a 12' x 6' area on the trailer floor and a 40' x 10' area on the parking lot. This was due to improper loading that caused the drums to be punctured by other freight during transit.

column168: Vehicle subject to random inspection at US border at Blue Water Bridge.  3 drums observed to have bungs that are believed to be inadequately closed resulting in minor amount of liquid waste leaking onto the container lid.  No liquid waste was released to surfaces other than the container lid and in one case the side of the drum.  The vehicle was returned to Canada, Sarnia; load fully inspected; containers properly closed, and any observed contamination removed with absorbents.  There were no other associated or external impacts or contamination.  Observed release believed to have occurred in the course of normal transportation.  No state report was made to Michigan.
column169: investigation undertaken.  Corrective action put in place including  1. Involved parties (consignor and transporter) have received retraining regarding proper containers, closures, and securement. (complete) 2. Subsequent haz mat loads subject to intensive oversight to ensure no reoccurrence. (Complete) 3. issuance of company wide alert to inform employees of issue, and corrective measures. (end Oct 2018) 4. Issuance of training and support to up-stream transporters and account managers.  (On going)

column168: During routine facility inspection, a transport trailer was identified as having a release. An internal response team was dispatched to assist with remediation. In proper personnel protective equipment, verified through the internal health and safety department, the response team was successful in identifying the compromised container, over-packing the container into an approved UN rated salvage drum and in remediation of the transport trailer and ground beneath. The impact of this release was contained to the transport trailer floor and concrete of the dock the transport trailer was staged on. A courtesy report to the Washington State Depart of Ecology was made to Michael McCain resulting in report number 684106. The container was shipped to its final destination without further incident.
column169: The container showed no signs of release during acceptance into transportation nor during routine facility weighing and staging. The cause of the puncture was not immediately identifiable. The facility Supervisor reviewed the incident with facility team and communicated the importance of being diligent and methodical when moving containers, in an effort to prevent releases.

column168: On 09/24/2018, SNLU 61961 was reported leaking upon deramp at BNSF San Bernardino IMF. The waybill lists that the unit was carrying hazardous material. In the interest of safety, the unit was placed on hold and moved to the containment pit pending interior for inspection. Approved contractor Ocean Blue was dispatched to remediate the leak at the facility. Interior inspection revealed 8     250 gallon totes stowed 1 high and 2 wide with tygard for doorway securement. The leaking material was deemed hazardous by Ocean Blue. The origin of the leak was throughout the load. The heat caused the totes to swell, 4 caps cracked and pop off. With the caps off the liquid was able to spill out of multiple containers. The material inside the 250 gallon totes was UN1760 THPS     Urea Precondensate (hazardous) and 1   2 gallons spilled out between the 4 totes. This incident has been deemed as shipper   s responsibility and all contractor cost from Ocean Blue will be billed directly to Schneider National. Cargo, parking space and haz pit was remediated by Ocean Blue. Holds have been released and unit is able to out gate.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Tank car UTLX953157 was found venting from the protective housing by Norfolk Southern personnel.  The car was being held due to being overloaded.  Upon inspection by a contractor, the source of the leak was the PRD.  A tank trunk was brought in to reduce the load.  The PRD ceased venting during the loading of the tank truck.

On 9/18/18 at approximately 10:22 CST, the UTLX 959227 was found during yard inspection to be releasing LPG from the protective housing.  BNSF Hazmat Responders isolated the area and inspected the car, finding a liquid line valve plug not installed with the valve partially open.  The valve was closed immediately, stopping the release.  Responders then properly tool tightened the plug to ensure that secondary closure was intact.  Release volumes are estimated based upon responder observations.  Additionally, the amount in the package is estimated as there is no way to know the actual residual amount of LPG in the car.  All released LPG dissipated to atmosphere.
column169: Shipper should review pre-shipment procedures to ensure that employees follow procedures.  All fittings should be tool tight prior to offering for transportation.(NAR:119)

column168: Upon arrival at the Burton, MI facility, a small drip was noticed on the front of the roll-off container. Upon inspection, a bad weld was found in the dog house area of the container near the hook. It is believed that the inside of the welded area was sharp enough to puncture the inner liner allowing some free liquid which had phase shifted from the material during transport to leak out. The leak was immediately treated with absorbents and the container placed into secondary containment to prevent further environmental impact. The material which had leaked onto the gravel parking area was treated, collected and disposed of properly. The remaining material in the container was transferred to another container and shipped to its final destination without further incident.

column168: Driver hooked up hose to load truck from well site. Driver went in the cab, was not present during loading operations and overfilled trailer 6051 around 10:45 on 09/23/2018 (based on truck tracking device). Driver did not report the release. A Scout Energy Pumper, or the lease operator discovered the spill at approximately 9am on 09/24/18. 42 barrels of product was released through the trailer vent line onto the lease. Product migrated to a nearby creek. Scout Energy reported the release to the OCC, who contacted Chuck Firth (BKEP - VP EH&S), who contacted Steve Whitaker (BKEP - Director of Trucking). BKEP notified the NRC immediately upon receiving notification of the incident.     Scout Energy began immediate spill containment and remediation of both the lease and creek. Scout Energy with a roustabout crew, backhoe, and vacuum truck, began remediation of the lease site on 09/24/18 upon discovery of oil. Scout Energy and crew set booms in the creek to contain the release. The majority of the oil was cleaned up/removed by Scout the day of discovery.  Gary Wilkins of BKEP Pipeline and consultants from P&H took over clean up and remediation of the creek on the morning of 09/25/18. A containment weir was constructed approximately 3/4 mile from release site down the creek.  Vacuum tucks were set periodically between the weir and the release location.  The creek was continuously flushed with fresh water from tanker trucks and the oil was sucked up. Booms and oil soak pads were used to clean up th remaining residue.  A total of 7.81 barrels were removed from the creek. Remediation of the creek was signed off on by OCC on 10/01/18.
column169: Emphasized DOT regulation(s) and BKEP requirement to be within 25' of the controls of a cargo tank during loading/unloading operations. Email sent to all Drivers. Reviewed with Field Supervisors and Field Techs during weekly meeting.     Review of this incident, causes, costs and impact. Review of loading/unloading procedures during the loading/unloading process during quarterly OT meetings.

column168: A MIDNIGHT P/T SUPERVISOR NOTICED THE LEAKING HAZMAT ON AN IRREG CART. HE NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I UTILIZED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. BECAUSE THE PACKAGE WAS CORROSIVE, I ALTERED MY PPE TO INCLUDE THE SILVER SHIELD INNER LINERS. I TESTED THE PH. I CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY. I THEN USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE LIQUID ON THE CART. I RETESTED THE PH TO ENSURE IT WAS WITHIN THE 6-9 NEUTRAL RANGE. I SOLIDIFIED THE REMAINING LIQUID. I SWEPT UP ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS  PUT THEM INTO ANOTHER LINED SPILL TRAY. I THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN I OPENED THE BOX, I FOUND THAT 1 BOTTLE WAS DENTED CRACKED.
LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PACKAGE CALLED IN. PICKED UP BY RESPONDER, TRANSPORTED TO HAZMAT AREA AND PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.

column168: On midnight of Sep 19th 2018, Driver YaYa zongo went to deliver the gasoline at 2 South Columbus Ave, Mount Vernon NY 10553.He was dropping the regular gasoline in the tank at gas station. he was almost done and he removed the fitting elbow from the ground without shutting off the compartment Valve on tanker side. Due to this error there was a spill of approximately 20 gallons. He cleaned the place with the spill pads and mop. and he left the gas station around 1.30 or 2.00 AM. As he left the gas station, the place was clean and dry. After that incident we received a call from fire department as there is a spill, The company need to get this cleaned up from a certified environmental company and provided the three closest environmental company. We called Castelton Environmental and they did the required clean up.
column169: We are doing an internal investigation to determine the factor that led to the spill/incident. Recommendation for retraining the driver while loading and unloading the product and safety procedure. The driver was given verbal instructions to be more careful while loading,unloading and to follow safety procedures all the time.

New Comments: The Damage HAZMAT was discovered and scanned on the OB shift and placed into the HAZMAT Cage. No communication sent  to rest of operation. Later discovered and subsequently entered late into SCMS.   Course of Action to prevent future failures: 1. All OPS Admin QA will be certified to process Damaged HAZMATs 2. Email detailing the incident in the event of a damage HAZMAT if discovered requiredto be sent to the entire station informing of the incident. 3. Daily Check by Ops Admin (QA) & Manager (Ops Mgr) will ensure cage is reviewed that any packages in HAZMAT are compliant. (Sort & P&D will serve as review/audit)

Original comments:  I'm quoting the manger who found it; I discovered a leaking package. I moved the leaking package along with some damages out of the way along with what looked like a bottle of bleach without the lid. I then went back with absorbent and put it down on the spill.  New Comments: ISSUE: The issue the station had was that a damaged Hazmat package was not handled per procedure and it was processed late.  ROOT CAUSES: When the package got damaged the manager Justin Howe neglected to handle the situation immediately due to him not managing his work area effectively. Also Justin used the wrong type of absorbent to clean the spill.  This could have made the situation more dangerous. Also to add to the issue, QA did not take the time to learn how to process damaged Hazmats when the main clerk Terence (who handles all damaged hazmats in the facility) was on vacation.  They had already been told that they need to learn how to process damaged hazmats and were given the procedures on how to accomplish this part of their job.  They failed to learn this information due to management not following up with the QA personnel on their training and no initiative by the QA employees.  There was no communication between QA and management to make sure this process was not a failure.  FOLLOW UP:  All QA personnel have 1 month to learn the hazmat procedure while working with Terence.  He will make sure the works with each admin on the morning sort.  He will show them previous damaged Hazmats already completed and walk them through the proper procedures.Jeremiah will be in charge of making sure all clerks on the evening sort are prepared to handle damaged hazmats.   Karl Fisher will be in charge of making sure all Ops Managers review damaged Hazmat procedures especially regarding spill clean up.  To fix the communication issue, effective 9/26/2018 all damaged packages, hazmat or not will be sent in an email with a short description of the damage and  the location of the package and the date it was placed in the damage area(s).

column168: ON FRIDAY, SEPTEMBER 7TH 2018 AT 2:46AM A SOUTHEASTERN FUEL TRANSPORT DRIVER, JEREMY LOGAN, CALLED AND REPORTED THAT HIS TRAILER TIPPED OVER AT THE LOCATION OF 1857 GORDON HWY, AUGUSTA, GA 30904. DRIVER STATED HE WAS OK AND HE ALREADY ALERTED THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES, AND WAS FOLLOWING OUR INCIDENT/ACCIDENT PROTOCOL. WHEN OUR DISPATCHER ARRIVED AT THE LOCATION IT WAS ROUGHLY 3:15AM, THE POLICE, FIREMEN, CHAUNCEY'S TOWING AND FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL WERE ALREADY AT THE SCENE. WE HAD TO GET A SECOND WRECKER OUT TO THE SCENE TO LIFT THE LOADED TRAILER. ALSO WE CALLED PALMETTO DIESEL REPAIR TO COME OUT TO THE SCENE TO BYPASS THE BELLY VALVE TO GET THEM OPEN AND DROP THE GAS AT LUCKY 7, AND PUMP THE OTHER THE OTHER FOUR COMPARTMENTS INTO ANOTHER TRAILER. AFTER ALL TEAMS WERE FINISHED AND EVERYTHING WAS CLEANED UP IT WAS ABOUT 9 AM. ONLY 20 GALLONS OF GASOLINE LEAKED OUT OF THE TANKER.
column169: KEEP ALL EMPLOYEES UP TO DATE ON ACCIDENT/INCIDENT PROCEDURES.

column168: During routine facility inspections, a container was identified as having a small release. In appropriate personal protective equipment, the response team was successful in repacking the material into approved UN rated containers. The containers were sent to its final destination without further incident. This release was contained to the transport trailer floor, with no impact to land, soil, water or storm drains. A courteous report was submitted to Michael McCain of the Washington Department of Ecology and state report number 684523 was generated.
column169: Facility personnel contacted the party responsible for the original packaging of the material and discussed proper techniques for packaging material into these containers. Local management retrained the team on better techniques to prevent events from happening in the future.

column168: DRIVER ARRIVES AT WARREN COUNTY WWTP WITH A BULK DELIVERY OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE AROUND 10:40 AM. DRIVER CALLED THE CONTRACT FOR THE COUNTY TO GET ACCESS TO FACILITY FROM LOCKED GATE AND TOLD HIM HIS BLEACH WAS READY FOR DELIVERY. HIS CONTACT WAS NOT ON SITE BUT AT AN OFFICE. HIS CONTACT NOTIFIED THE WWTP OPERATOR THAT DRIVER WAS WAITING OUTSIDE. DRIVER GAINED ACCESS ABOUT 15 MINUTES LATER. DRIVER ASKED OPERATOR IF THE OPEN DOORS IS WHERE HE IS TO CONNECT AND OPERATOR STATED YES. DRIVER MADE CONNECTIONS AROUND 11:05 AND BEGAN HIS DELIVERY. DRIVER WENT BACK TO THE BANK TO CHECK ON FLOW AND THEN BACK TO TRUCK TO TURN THE FLOW OF THE MATERIAL DOWN AND NOTICED THE CHLORINE VAPORS ESCAPING A VENT PIPE OUTSIDE. DRIVER PROMPTLY SHUT THE VALVE FROM THE TANKER TO THE HOSE AND SHUT THE COMPRESSOR OFF AND EVACUATED WITH WWTP OPERATOR AT 11:15.  DRIVER HAD CONNECTED HIS SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE TO THE CUSTOMER HFS TANK AND VIOLENT REACTION TOOK PLACE RELEASING CHLORINE GAS TO THE ATMOSPHERE.
column169: EMPLOYEE IS NO LONGER EMPLOYED WITH THE COMPANY. WARREN COUNTY WATER HAS IMPLEMENTED NEW PROCEDURES FOR RECEIVING MATERIAL INTO THEIR FACILITY AND HAS ADDED ADDITIONAL SIGN-AGE TO INLETS TO THEIR TANKS. CHEMICALS INCORPORATED IS ALSO REVIEWING OTHER SITES IN WHICH THEY ARE DELIVERING MATERIAL IN THE SAME MANNER THIS WAS DELIVERED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. RIGHT SIDE WHEELS OF THE VEHICLE LEFT THE ROADWAY AND ENTERED INTO DITCH, DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO CORRECT BUT WAS NOT SUCCESSFUL. THE UNIT TIPPED AND SLID INTO THE DITCH. AS A  RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER WERE RELEASED ONTO THE ROADWAY AND INTO THE DITCH. THE FREE LIQUID ALSO REACHED THE DRIVER. THE DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTED BY AMBULANCE TO ALTRU HOSPITAL WITH LIFE THREATENING INJURIES. DRIVER WAS THEN TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER MEDICAL FACILITY WHERE HE LATER DIED. STRATA CORPORATION OF GRAND FORKS, ND WAS DISPATCHED TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP. STRATA CORPORATION REMOVED THE FREE LIQUID FROM THE IMPACTED ROADWAY AND EXCAVATED CONTAMINATED SOIL FROM THE IMPACTED DITCH LINE. STRATA CORPORATION COORDINATED DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: THE C&J VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING WEST ON COUNTY ROAD 431, WHEN THE DRIVER MOMENTARILY BECAME FIXATED ON THE RIGHT SIDE REAR VIEW MIRROR. AT THE TIME, THE DRIVER WAS DRIVING WITH HIS LEFT HAND ON THE STEERING WHEEL. WITH THE DRIVER'S ATTENTION ON THE MIRROR, THE DRIVER INADVERTENTLY MOVED THE STEERING WHEEL TO THE RIGHT. THIS MOVEMENT CAUSED THE VEHICLE TO TRAVEL OFF THE MAIN TRAVELED PORTION OF THE ROADWAY, AND TRAVELED DOWN THE EMBANKMENT ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROADWAY. THE DRIVER THEN OVER-CORRECTED BACK TO THE LEFT CAUSING THE TRAILER TO JACKKNIFE. AT THAT POINT THE DRIVER LOST TOTAL CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE. THE VEHICLE THEN ROLLED OVER ONTO IT'S RIGHT SIDE AND THEN ON ITS TOP SPILLING A PORTION OF THE CARGO, CAUSING SOME OF THE PACKAGES TO FAIL.  THE LEPC ESTABLISHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMMAND POST AND EVACUATED PERSONNEL WITHIN A APPROXIMATE 0.5 MILE RADIUS. A HAZMAT CREW TEAM WAS DISPATCHED AND SECURED THE HAZARDOUS CARGO. THE HAZMAT TEAM COMPLETED THE SECUREMENT OF THE HAZARDOUS CARGO WITHIN FOUR HOURS OF THE INCIDENT. AFTER SECUREMENT OF THE HAZARDOUS CARGO, THE SCENE WAS RELEASED BACK TO THE COMPANY AND RECOVERY OF THE VEHICLE AND REMAINING NON-HAZARDOUS CARGO COMMENCED. AFTER RECOVERY OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETED, REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES BEGAN AND REMAIN ONGOING.
column169: THE DRIVER WILL BE REQUIRED TO COMPLETE A DECISION DRIVING CLASS. IN ADDITION THE DRIVER MUST PASS A WRITTEN EXAM AND TAKE A COMMENTARY DRIVING TEST BEFORE BEING ALLOWED TO RESUME DRIVING DUTIES. AT THE NEXT FACILITY SAFETY STAND-DOWN, THE DRIVER WILL CONDUCT A BRIEFING ON THE INCIDENT AND LEAD A DISCUSSION ON WAYS TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS TYPE.

column14: US 31 BYPASS, 1 MILE N ST RD 2
column168: GOOD TRANSPORTATION HAD A GASOLINE TANK TRUCK, SEMI-TRACTOR UNIT #20 AND TRAILER #006 WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON THE US HWY 20 BYPASS, WHEN THE DRIVER HEARD A POP NOISE AS HE PASSED OVER EDISON ROAD. HE PULLED TO THE SIDE OF THE ROADWAYS SOON AS HE COULD, BUT DUE TO EXISTING CONSTRUCTION ZONE, HE DROVE TO THE END OF THE ZONE WHICH WAS BARRELED AND DISCOVERED A TIRE FIRE ON THE SEMI-TRAILER. HE ATTEMPTED TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE WITH THE UNIT'S FIRE EXTINGUISHER, BUT WAS NOT ABLE TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE. HE IMMEDIATELY CALLED 911 TO INITIATE A RESPONSE FROM THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. BASED ON THE FIRE REPORT, THE DISPATCH TIME WAS 0435 AND ENGINE 11 ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 0449 HOURS. THE CAD REPORT INDICATES THAT AT 0440 HOURS THE TIRES WERE ON FIRE, BUT THE FLAMES WERE SPREADING UP THE SIDE OF THE TANK TRUCK. BY 0500 HOURS, IT WAS REPORTED AS A FULLY INVOLVED TANKER FIRE AND EVACUATIONS WERE ORDERED. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THERE IS NO DOCUMENTATION OF THE NUMBER CIVILIAN EVACUATIONS IN THE COUNTY POLICE OR SOUTH BEND FIRE REPORTS. AT 0631 HOURS, FIRE COMMAND ADVISED EVACUEES MAY RETURN TO THEIR HOMES. EVACUATIONS ESTIMATED AT 1.5 HOURS. FIVE HOMES WERE IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA.  ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP CONTRACTOR WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD ALREADY CONTACTED SUNPRO ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES AND THEY HAD RECOVERED SIX DRUMS OF GASOLINE CONTAMINATED WATER AND ONE DRUM OF DIESEL FROM THE SEMI-TRACTOR'S FUEL TANK. AFTER COLLECTION OF FREE PRODUCTS AND STABILIZATION OF THE SCENE, SUNPRO WAS RELIEVED. IES BEGAN THE RECOVERY PROCESS AND CONTACTED A WRECKER SERVICE TO REMOVE ALL DEBRIS. IES CONFIRMED WITH INDOT OFFICIALS THAT DUE TO THE INTENSE HEAT, THE ROADWAY WOULD REMAIN CLOSED UNTIL THE AFFECTED AREAS COULD BE MILLED AND NEW ASPHALT LAID. A LOCAL PAVING CONTRACTOR WAS ABLE TO MILL THE SOUTHBOUND LANES BY 0930 THE NEXT MORNING. NEW ASPHALT WAS LAID AND PAINT STRIPPING OCCURRED. THE SOUTHBOUND LANES WERE REOPENED AT 1930.
column169: GOOD TRANSPORTATION IS IMPLEMENTING A THREE TIER APPROACH TO SCHEDULED INSPECTIONS. THE FIRST INSPECTION (LEVEL A) WILL CONSIST OF HAVING TH UNIT BROUGHT TO THE SHOP TO BE VISUALLY INSPECTED BY THE MECHANIC. THE NEXT INSPECTION (LEVEL B) WILL BE A LITTLE MORE IN DEPTH THAT WILL INCLUDE THE VISUAL INSPECTION AND CHECKING ALL FLUID LEVELS. THE NEXT INSPECTION (LEVEL C) WILL CONSIST OF A FULL BLOWN SERVICE INCLUDING CHANGING OILS & FILTERS, GETTING UNDER THE TRUCK LOOKING FOR ISSUES, CHECKING BRAKES, ECT. THE INTERVALS FOR THE SERVICES ARE A: 10,000 MILES, B: 15,000 MILES AND C: 25,000 MILES. GOOD TRANSPORTATION WILL ALSO IMPLEMENT ANY NEW DRIVER HIRE, TO SPEND FOUR HOURS IN THE SHOP WITH THE MECHANIC GOING OVER THE PROPER METHODS TO PERFORM PRE & POST TRIP INSPECTIONS AND ANY MAINTENANCE ITEMS TO LOOK FOR DURING INSPECTIONS AND WALK AROUND.

column168: DRIVER WAS GOING 62 MPH IN A 55 MPH CURVE ZONE ON I-279 SOUTHBOUND INTO PITTSBURGH AND THE LOAD SHIFTED IN THE TANKER TRAILER AND HE LOST CONTROL AS HE TRIED TO CORRECT OR OVER CORRECT AND TURNED THE TANK ON THE SIDE AND RAN THE GUARDRAIL DOWN THE HIGHWAY AND EVENTUALLY THE TRACTOR TIPPED ON THE PASSENGER SIDE AS WELL. THAN TANKER TRAILER RIPPED OPEN A HOLE IN COMPARTMENT #1 WHICH THE GROUND KEPT SEALED UP SOMEWHAT ACCORDING TO THE ENVIRONMENTAL TEAM CLEAN UP. ANOTHER HOLE WAS IN COMPARTMENT #5 AROUND 2/3 OF THE WAY DOWN AND THIS WAS THE MAJOR RELEASE OF FLUIDS UNTIL REACHING THE EDGE OF THE HOLE OF SPILLED ANTIFREEZE. THE RELEASE TIME WOULD BE ABOUT 5 HOURS AS THEY MOVED TO REMOVE ALL REMAINING FLUIDS FROM THE TRAILER WITH A VAC TRUCK. COMPARTMENT #1 AGAIN HAD THE SLOW LEAK AS THE GROUND SOMEWHAT PLUGGED IT.  THE DRIVER CALLED IN TO OUR OFFICE TO OUR SUPERVISORS AND THE VICE PRESIDENT. CALLS WERE MADE TO BRING IN EMS, STATE TROOPERS, HAZMAT TEAM, SPILL RESPONSE INSURANCE TEAM TO MAKE CONTACT AND CONFIRM AT THE SITE ACTIONS WERE IN PLACE TO LIMIT EXPOSURE TO THE ENVIRONMENT AND HUMAN CONTACT. WE SPOKE WITH THE DOT ON 9/11/18 CONFIRMING THE INCIDENT BUT THE OWNER WAS NOT GIVEN AN INCIDENT NUMBER.
column169: WE WILL CONTINUE TO USE OUR GPS SYSTEM TO MONITOR HARD BRAKING AND EXCESSIVE SPEED ON THE HIGHWAYS WITH OUR DRIVERS. WE WILL WORK WITH THE DRIVER INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT TO UNDERSTAND THE OVERALL SITUATION AND GO OVER SPEEDING IN A CURVE ZONE. HIS DRIVING SKILLS WILL BE EVACUATED AND A DECISION WILL BE MADE ON WHAT FUTURE DRIVING OF TRACTOR AND TRAILER COMBINATIONS HE WILL BE ALLOWED TO DRIVE OR HE MAY BE MOVED TO A BOX TRUCK.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While in transit, driver noticed possible leak from the container. Driver pulled off of the roadway to inspect the container and confirmed small leak coming from the container. Evergreen AES was dispatched to inspect the trailer and perform the required cleanup. Evergreen AES arrived and inspected the leaking container. Evergreen AES discovered one(1) leaking 55-gallon drum. Drum had a small pin hole in the bottom. Evergreen AES did not discover reason for damage to the drum. Evergreen AES over-packed the leaking drum and deployed absorbent material to contain the free liquid on the impacted trailer floor. Evergreen AES removed a small amount of contaminated dirt from underneath the leaking container. One drum of spent absorbent material and contaminated dirt was generated as a result of the cleanup. The over-pack drum containing the leaking drum was left on the container. Evergreen AES will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the cleanup.
column169: Since the release was accidental , no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence. However, XPO Drayage, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

On September 27, 2018, United Vision Logistics was involved in a rollover accident in Hallettsville, TX. It was reported that the cargo tanker was carrying a Hazardous, UN3082 material, that turned over and ended up in a ditch. The speed of the driver is unknown. The driver was able to get the top catch closed to prevent further impact. Contractors arrived onsite and at 1000 ET, confirmed approximately 100-gallons released from the dome lid of the iso tank because it was not tightened properly. At 1143 ET, Contractors reported that 70-gallons were recovered from the ditch and placed into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. Absorbent was applied to the ditch to solidify the residual. At 1224 ET, Contractors confirmed the product was successfully trans-loaded to a relief tank. The impacted 10' x 20' area was secured with poly sheeting. At 1258 ET, Contractors transported (3) drums of waste and departed site. On October 3, 2018, Contractors arrived back on site at 0930 ET to complete remediation. The soil was excavated, back-filled and seeded. An estimated 17 yards of impacted soil was removed. At 1356 ET, Contractors completed all remediation activities.

column168: During highway transit, (1) 12 ounce metal aerosol can released approximately 4 ounces of material through the valve stem due to building pressure within the can. The reason for the building pressure within the can is unknown.  XPO Logistics terminal personnel found the spillage within the cardboard over-packaging box. The cardboard over-packaging box contains a total of (12) 12 ounce metal aerosol cans. The spillage impacted the entire package's contents. None of the spillage escaped the over-packaging box.  XPO Logistics terminal personnel called Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) for guidance on how to properly handle the hazardous materials spillage. ERTS instructed them to take the entire cardboard over-package box and place into (1) 10-gallon metal drum and staged it their OS&D for proper disposal.

column168: On September 27, 2018, at 0939 ET, Schneider Bulk Carriers reported a tanker release to ERTS that  occurred on September 27, 2018 at 0930 ET. It was reported that due to an internal valve failure, UN1814 Potassium Hydroxide released from a 1200-gallon tanker. The driver contained the release with plastic buckets until a response team could arrive. At 1235 ET, contractors arrived onsite and utilized the drivers diaphragm pump on the leaking valve to unload the tanker and transfer into Schneider's relief trailer onsite. Floor dry and neutralizer were used to clean the impacted asphalt. At 1330 ET, contractors indicated that 2-gallons released to a 45' x 10' area of the pavement. It was also stated that (2) 55-gallon poly drums, (2) 5-gallon, and (1) 1-gallon poly buckets of product was  collected. At 1710 ET, contractors stated the transfer was complete. An estimated 60-gallons released in total but only approximately 2-gallons released to the pavement. Contractors utilized acidic degreaser to had a final pH reading of 7. Absorbents were worked into the asphalt and collected. At 1915 ET, contractors completed cleanup. The impacted asphalt was neutralized between 7-9 pH. A total of (3) 55-gallon poly drums of waste was generated. At 2000 ET, contractors departed site. All waste was staged onsite for Schneider personnel to manage and to be picked up at a later date.

column168: A STEEL ROLL-OFF, LINED WITH A PLASTIC LINER, WAS LOADED WITH APPROXIMATELY 22,600 POUNDS OF ETP FILTER PRESS CAKE. WHILE THE CONTAINER CAPACITY IS 40,000 POUNDS, A LESSER AMOUNT WAS LOADED BECAUSE THE FILTER PRESS CAKE HAD A HIGHER THAN NORMAL WATER CONTENT DUE TO OPERATIONAL PROBLEMS AT THE GENERATING FACILITY.  ONCE THE ROLL-OFF WAS LOADED, A TARP COVER WAS SECURED OVER THE LOAD WITH FLEXIBLE (BUNGEE) CORDS PRIOR TO SHIPPING. THERE WERE NO ISSUES WITH THE LOAD DURING LOADING. THE LOAD WAS TRANSPORTED APPROXIMATELY 1/2 MILE TO THE HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES FACILITY. THERE WERE NO ISSUES WITH THE LOAD DURING TRANSPORT. DURING UNLOADING, THE DRIVER LOWERED THE ROLL-OFF CONTAINER TO THE GROUND USING A CABLE MECHANISM ON THE TRUCK. WHEN THE ROLL-OFF CAME INTO CONTACT WITH THE GROUND, THE CONTENTS OF THE LOAD SHIFTED SUFFICIENTLY TO PUSH AGAINST THE COVER, BREAKING THE FLEXIBLE CORDS AND SPILLING OVER THE EDGE OF THE ROLL-OFF. THE ROLL-OFF CONTAINER, THE INNER PLASTIC LINER, AND THE ROLL-OFF COVER WERE UNDAMAGED. THE RELEASE OF MATERIAL WAS VERY SHORT IN DURATION (1-2 SECONDS), AND APPROXIMATELY 200-300 POUNDS IN WEIGHT. HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES PERSONNEL WERE ON-SITE AND RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY, PLACING THE RELEASED MATERIAL AND IMPACTED GRAVEL FROM THE LOT INTO FOUR (4) DRUMS.
column169: QUEMETCO WILL REVIEW ITS PACKAGING PROCEDURES WITH ALL PERSONNEL INVOLVED IN LOADING AND TRANSPORT OF THIS MATERIAL. QUEMETCO WILL REVIEW ITS PACKAGING METHOD FOR THIS MATERIAL AND CONSIDER OTHER TYPES OF PACKAGING.

ON 9/11/2018 AT 11:58 AM, KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY'S (KCS) ENVIRONMENTAL AND HAZMAT DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED THAT FRA INSPECTOR RAYMOND DIEHL HAD TAKEN ISSUE WITH TANK CAR UTLX 649198 (CLASS 8, UN3265) AT THE KCS BATON ROUGE YARD. MR. DIEHL OBSERVED UTLX 649198 WITH A SUSPECTED HAZMAT RELEASE FROM THE MANWAY, AND PRODUCT RESIDUE ON BOTH SIDES OF THE CAR.  KCS MOBILIZED A RAILROAD QUALIFIED HAZMAT RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE AND RESPOND. UPON ARRIVAL, THE CONTRACTOR FOUND ALL MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS TO BE TOOL TIGHT. AFTER OPENING THE MANWAY, THE GASKET INSTALLED ON THE MANWAY LID WAS FOUND TO BE IN ACCEPTABLE CONDITION; HOWEVER, UPON REMOVING THE GASKET, EVIDENCE OF PRODUCT WAS FOUND BETWEEN THE MANWAY LID AND THE LID GASKET. BASED ON THESE FINDINGS, IT IS SUSPECTED THAT THE BOLTS WERE NOT TIGHTENED EVENLY, CAUSING LIFT ON ONE SIDE OF THE MANWAY AND A MISALIGNED GASKET. A NEW RIM NOZZLE GASKET WAS INSTALLED TO ENSURE A PROPER SEAL, THE MANWAY WAS CLOSED, AND THE BOLTS TIGHTENED TOOL TIGHT. ALL OTHER CLOSURES WERE CHECKED AND FOUND SECURE. THE OUTSIDE OF THE CAR WAS SUBSEQUENTLY DECONTAMINATED BEFORE THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION.  FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

column168: TRACTOR/SEMI-TANK CARRYING 3800 GAL. CAUSTIC SODA 50% WAS WESTBOUND WILLOW ST. WITH CURVE IN THE ROAD. UNVERIFIED CAR SWERVED INTO LANE GOING EASTBOUND. TRUCK/TRAILER MOVED OVER TO AVOID CAR. TRAILER WHEELS WENT OFF THE ROAD ONTO SOFT DIRT CAUSING PRODUCT SLOSH AND FLIPPER TRAILER. ACCIDENT CAUSED DUE TO DRIVER EXCESS SPEED, UNVERIFIED SECOND CAR AND SPEED LIMIT OF ROAD. APPROXIMATELY 50 GAL. SPILLED FROM AIR RELIEF VALVE WHEN THE FORCE OF THE TRAILER CRASHING ON ITS SIDE CAUSING THE VALVE TO POP OPEN BEFORE RESEALING ITSELF. TRAILER CAME TO REST ON ITS SIDE WITH REAR OF TRAILER DOWN AN EMBANKMENT. VACUUM TRUCK WAS USED OF OFFLOAD PRODUCT FROM REAR OF TRAILER. AFTER OFF-LOADING 1500 GAL. THE TRAILER WAS UP-RIGHTED BY CRANES AND FINISHED OFF-LOADING PRODUCT. APPROXIMATELY 20 GAL. DIESEL FUEL SPILLED FROM FUEL TANK ON TRACTOR. FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON SITE WITHIN 10 MIN. column168: On 9/18/18 at approximately 10:22 CST, the UTLX 959227 was found during yard inspection to be releasing LPG from the protective housing.  BNSF Hazmat Responders isolated the area and inspected the car, finding a liquid line valve plug not installed with the valve partially open.  The valve was closed immediately, stopping the release.  Responders then properly tool tightened the plug to ensure that secondary closure was intact.  Release volumes are estimated based upon responder observations.  Additionally, the amount in the package is estimated as there is no way to know the actual residual amount of LPG in the car.  All released LPG dissipated to atmosphere.
column169: Shipper should review pre-shipment procedures to ensure that employees follow procedures.  All fittings should be tool tight prior to offering for transportation.(NAR:119)

column168: On 09/24/2018, SNLU 61961 was reported leaking upon deramp at BNSF San Bernardino IMF. The waybill lists that the unit was carrying hazardous material. In the interest of safety, the unit was placed on hold and moved to the containment pit pending interior for inspection. Approved contractor Ocean Blue was dispatched to remediate the leak at the facility. Interior inspection revealed 8 -250 gallon totes stowed 1 high and 2 wide with tygard for doorway secured. The leaking material was deemed hazardous by Ocean Blue. The origin of the leak was throughout the load. The heat caused the totes to swell, 4 caps cracked and pop off. With the caps off the liquid was able to spill out of multiple containers. The material inside the 250 gallon totes was UN1760 THPS Urea PreCondensate (hazardous) and 1 -2 gallons spilled out between the 4 totes. This incident has been deemed as shipper's responsibility and all contractor cost from Ocean Blue will be billed directly to Schneider National. Cargo, parking space and haz pit was remediated by Ocean Blue. Holds have been released and unit is able to out gate.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Note: the tank trailer was not damaged in this accident. Preliminary investigation reveals traffic was stopped on Interstate 75 north bound due to an injury accident at mile marker 43 that the Laurel County Sheriff's Department was investigating. Due to the roadway narrowing from three (3) lanes to two (2) lanes and the roadway ahead was partially blocked, it resulted in stopped or slowly moving traffic for several minutes. Unit 1 was traveling north bound on Interstate 75 and struck Unit 2 in the rear causing a complete over ride as Unit 2 was stopped. The initial point of impact occurred in the far right hand lane parallel with the on-ramp. Both units then struck unit 3 in the rear also in the far right lane resulting in a domino effect of each unit thereafter striking the unit in front of them, all in the right hand lane. As unit 3 struck unit 4, unit 4 struck unit 5 and unit 5 struck unit 6. During these impacts, unit 1 was veering toward the center concrete barrier and ultimately struck the concrete divider striking a sign and maintaining contact with the barrier for approximately five hundred (500) yards until final rest.

column168: Driver was driving north on hwy 270 loaded with gasoline it was at the beginning of the work zone starting just a mile south of hwy 51. It was drizzling and was still dark the road does not have any reflectors to distinguish your middle or outside lines and with the rain without that it is not visible to see the road. Approaching the construction bypass driver did not have a visibility on the road and had about 4 or 5 car coming on the opposite lane headed south there for blinding him even more.  Driver tried to move truck to edge and thinking of not hitting anyone causing the front passenger tire to drop off road into mud driver was not able to bring truck back up to pavement and turn a full turn on it’s side, road had no shoring or shoulder there was a slope of about 10 to 12 foot
column169: In construction zone driver was traveling at 37mph when front right steer tire went off a 14" drop off, the road striping was not reflective and driver could not tell how far over he was to edge of highway. Speed zone in construction zone at time was 45mph. Driver came to complete stop with only the passenger side tires off pavement. As driver was attempting to release seatbelt, product in tank during slosh effect caused entire unit to roll onto passenger side. Unit was not moving when rollover occurred and no skid marks on ground reflected otherwise. Construction crew advised that they had asked Oklahoma Dept of Transportation officials to be able to place reflective tape or cones on edge of highway to show a drop off and was told it wouldn't be necessary. It is the belief after investigation that should either had been available driver would have known how close to edge of roadway he was.

column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, FLAMMABLE, N.O.S., WITH FLASH POINT ABOVE 37.8 C, AT OR ABOVE ITS FLASH POINT
column62: Misaligned Material, Component, or Device; Human Error
column168: AT 09:55 ON THE MORNING OF SEPTEMBER 28, 2018 STOLTHAVEN HOUSTON OPERATIONS PERSONNEL OPENED THE 3-INCH PRODUCT FILL LINE & BEGAN LOADING RAIL CAR TILX 210129 SPOTTED AT RACK R-1 AT THE STOLTHAVEN HOUSTON TERMINAL WITH LIQUID P-DICHLOROBENZENE ("PDCB") DISCHARGING FROM STORAGE TANK A20-1. THE OPERATOR IN CHARGE OF LOADING INTENDED TO OPEN THE VAPOR VALVE ON THE RAIL CAR TO VENT THE CAR DURING FILLING; HOWEVER, THE 2-INCH PRODUCT UNLOADING VALVE, WHICH HAS A DIP-TUBE TO THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR, WAS MISTAKENLY OPENED INSTEAD OF THE VENT VALVE, WHICH REMAINED CLOSED. NOTE THAT PDCB HAS A FREEZE POINT OF APPROXIMATELY 127 FAHRENHEIT & IS A SOLID AT AMBIENT TEMPERATURES; PDCB IS HEATED DURING STORAGE & TRANSFERS AT STOLTHAVEN HOUSTON TO FACILITATE PRODUCT MOVEMENT. RAIL CARS RECEIVED FOR PDCB LOADING OFTEN CONTAIN RESIDUAL, SOLIDIFIED PDCB PRODUCT IN THE SUMP AREA & ALSO IN THE DIP-TUBE. THE DIP-TUBE IN TILX 210129 WAS PLUGGED WITH SOLIDIFIED PDCB AT THE START OF LOADING, WHICH PREVENTED THE RAIL CAR FROM VENTING PROPERLY. ONCE THIS RESIDUAL, SOLIDIFIED PDCB IN THE DIP-TUBE MELTED AS THE CAR FILLED WITH HOT PDCB FROM TANK A20-1, THE BUILT-UP PRESSURE IN THE CAR RELEASED THROUGH THE DIP-TUBE & OPEN 2-INCH VALVE, CAUSING LIQUID PDCB TO SPRAY FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. THE CAR WAS SECURED AT APPROXIMATELY 10:30. THE RELEASED PDCB WAS CONTAINED ON-SITE & NO NAVIGABLE WATERWAYS WERE THREATENED BY THIS RELEASE. STOLTHAVEN HOUSTON'S OIL SPILL RESPONSE ORGANIZATION ("OSRO") WAS NOTIFIED OF THIS INCIDENT & MOBILIZED A CREW TO THE FACILITY TO PERFORM THE NECESSARY CLEAN-UP & RESPONSE EFFORTS. THE RELEASED PDCB PRODUCT SOLIDIFIED QUICKLY AS IT COOLED, WHICH ASSISTED IN CLEAN-UP OF THE AFFECTED AREAS.  NOTE THAT AT THE TIME OF THIS EVENT RAIL CAR TILX 210129 WAS STATIONARY & LOADING AT THE STOLTHAVEN HOUSTON TERMINAL, THE CAR WAS NOT CONNECTED TO ANY MOTIVE FORCE, & IT HAD NOT YET BEEN OFFERED FOR TRANSPORTATION. THERE WAS NO -FF-SITE IMPACT, NO INJURIES, AND NO EQUIPMENT DAMAGE AS A RESULT OF THIS EVENT.
column169: WHILE THE VALVES ON RAIL CAR TILX 210129 WERE LABELED CORRECTLY, THESE LABELS WERE IN POOR CONDITION AND WERE DIFFICULT TO READ. FURTHERMORE, THE VALVE ARRANGEMENT VARIES BETWEEN THE DIFFERENT CUSTOMER RAIL CARS THAT ARE LOADED WITH PDCB AT THE STOLTHAVEN HOUSTON TERMINAL. HUMAN ERROR LED TO THE INCORRECT VALVE BERING OPENED WHEN ATTEMPTING TO VENT THE CAR DURING PDCB LOADING; THE TASK WAS PERFORMED BASED ON MEMORY INSTEAD OF READING THE VALVE LABELS. STOLTHAVEN HOUSTON OPERATIONS MANAGEMENT WILL HOLD AN AWARENESS SESSION WITH OPERATIONS DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL TO REVIEW RAIL CAR VALVE ARRANGEMENT & THE FUNCTION OF EACH CONNECTION POINT. STOLTHAVEN HOUSTON'S PDCB CUSTOMER WILL ALSO BE CONTACTED TO IMPROVE RAIL CAR VALVE CONFIGURATION LABELS & TO IMPLEMENT A COLOR CODED SYSTEM TO IMPROVE VALVE RECOGNITION. LASTLY, STOLTHAVEN HOUSTON WILL SHARE THE LESSONS LEARNED FROM THIS INCIDENT WITH OTHER STOLTHAVEN TERMINAL LOCATIONS.   NOTE THAT AS OF THE DATE OF THIS REPORT. STOLTHAVEN HOUSTON HAS NOT RECEIVED FINAL INVOICES FOR EITHER (1) THE SPILL RESPONSE EFFORTS COMPLETED BY OUR OSRP OR (2) THE WASTE DISPOSAL COSTS FOR THE TWO ROLL-OFF BOXES USED TO COLLECT THE SPILL CLEAN-UP MATERIAL S; THESE BOXES REMAIN ON-SITE FOR SAMPLING SO THAT A PROPER WASTE PROFILE CAN BE DEVELOPED PRIOR TO OFF-SITE DISPOSAL. AS SUCH, THE "REMEDIATION/CLEAN-UP" DAMAGES LISTED IN ITEM #32 ARE A BEST AVAILABLE ESTIMATE AT THIS TIME.

column168: TRUCK WAS LOADED FROM FRONT TO BACK WITH PALLETS TIGHTLY. BATTERIES STRAPPED TO PALLETS AT FLOOR LEVEL, STACKED 2 BATTERIES HIGH ON A PALLET, 6 BATTERIES PER PALLET, 28 PALLETS IN THE TRAILER. TOTAL HEIGHT OF LOAD WAS 14 INCHES HIGH. WHILE IN TRANSIT, THE TRUCK ENCOUNTERED A LOAD SHIFT THROWING 3 PALLETS FORWARD FROM THE REAR OF THE TRUCK. THE SAFETY PRECAUTIONS, SUCH AS SPACERS AND POST PROTECTORS, WERE DAMAGED CAUSING BATTERIES TO SPARK AND IGNITE. LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED TO THE FIRE. THE FIRE BURNED FOR ROUGHLY 30-35 MINUTES. WHEN THE TRUCK DRIVER WAS ASKED HOW THE LOAD SHIFTED, THE DRIVER DID NOT RESPOND WITH AN ANSWER.
column169: 1. TRAIN EMPLOYEES ON DOT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL 2. FIND A BETTER WAY TO PACKAGE BATTERIES FOR RECYCLING 3. RECYCLING COMPANY HAS TOLD US THEY WILL NO LONGER USE THE SERVICES OF FREIGHT COWBOY

column168: DRIVER OF TRACTOR TRAILER CARRYING 7976 GALLONS OF ETHANOL WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND IN THE RIGHT LANE OF HWY. 61 NEAR HWY. OO IN EOLIA, MO (PIKE COUNTY). AN INTOXICATED DRIVER OF A 2009 DODGE JOURNEY IN THE PASSING LANE VEERED INTO THE RIGHT LANE STRIKING THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TRACTOR TRAILER AND FORCING THE TRACTOR TRAILER OFF THE ROADWAY AND INTO A DITCH, WHERE IT OVERTURNED THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE A TOTAL LOSS, AND THE TRUCK DRIVER SUSTAINED SEVERE INJURIES.  WITNESSES STOPPED AND CALLED 911. WHILE WAITING, THEY PULLED THE TRUCK DRIVER FROM THE WRECKAGE. RESPONDING WERE THE PIKE COUNTY SHERIFF AND EOLIA COMMUNITY FIRE DEPARTMENT, AS WELL AS FIRE DEPARTMENTS OF BOWLING GREEN, HANNIBAL, PIKE COUNTY, WENTZVILL, AND O'FALLON; AIR EVAC AND MO STATE HIGHWAY PATROL. FROESEL OIL DISPATCHER WAS CALLED, WHO RESPONDED TO SCENE TO ASSIST AND ALSO CALLED DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATION. SAND DIKES WERE BUILT AND INFLATABLE SWIMMING POOLS WERE EMPLOYED TO CAPTURE LEAKING FUEL.  FUEL LEAKED FOR 7-8 HOURS FROM SEVERAL LOCATIONS ON THE FUEL TANK: FRONT BULKHEAD RIPPED OPEN (HOLE SIZE OF BASKETBALL), BACK BULKHEAD BROKEN OPEN, 3" HOLE IN COMPARTMENT #2, HOLE IN SIDE OF TANK, HOLE IN BOTTOM OF TANK.  FUEL LOAD WAS A TOTAL LOSS.
column169: NOTHING SPECIFIC. DRUNK DRIVER AT FAULT.

column168: WE (CARRIER) LOADED MOLTEN SULFUR AT ST. PAUL PARK REFINERY IN MN. MOLTEN SULFUR WAS LOADED @ 290 DEGREES. CARRIER DROVE TO ADM IN MARSHALL MN. CARRIER HOOKED UP HOSE TO TRAILER AND ADM TANK. ADM PLANT COMPRESSED AIR IS USED TO PRESSURIZE THE TRAILER TO OFFLOAD MOLTEN SULFUR. ADM PLANT AIR WAS HOOKED TO TRAILER AND CARRIER OPENED REAR OUTLET VALVE. MOLTEN SULFUR FLOWED INTO HOSE AND DIDN'T MOVE THROUGHOUT THE HOSE. MOLTEN SULFUR COOLED AND JAMMED HOSE. EITHER PLANT DIDN'T HAVE THEIR VALVE OPEN OR PLANT AIR WAS NOT WORKING. HOSE WAS FULL OF SET-UP SULFUR. A SMALL AMOUNT OF ALMOST SET-UP SULFUR SPILLED OUT OF HOSE WHEN IT WAS UNHOOKED.
column169: ADM PLANT SHOULD PROVE TO CARRIER DRIVER THAT THEIR AIR IS WORKING BEFORE REAR PRODUCT VALVE IS OPENED. WHEN REAR PRODUCT VALVE ON TRAILER IS OPENED YOU HAVE LITTLE FINE TO OFF-LOAD PRODUCT BEFORE IT COOLS AND SETS-UP TO A SOLID.
